fry\n|mosquitofish,mosquito fish\n|mousefish\n|mudfish\n|muttonfish\n|needlefish\n|neither fish, flesh, nor fowl\n|neither fish, flesh, nor good red herring,neither fish nor flesh, nor good red herring\n|neither fish nor flesh\n|neither fish nor fowl\n|nonfish\n|noodlefish\n|numbfish\n|nurseryfish\n|oarfish\n|odd fish\n|oilfish\n|one man's fish is another man's poison,one man's fish is another man's poisson\n|only dead fish go with the flow\n|other fish in the sea\n|outfish\n|overfish\n|oysterfish\n|paddlefish\n|paleofish\n|panfish,pan fish\n|paradisefish\n|parrotfish\n|pearlfish\n|penfish\n|pigfish\n|pinfish\n|pipefish\n|platyfish\n|plunderfish\n|pondfish\n|poolfish\n|porcupinefish\n|pricklefish\n|pufferfish,puff-fish\n|pupfish\n|purple-fish\n|queenfish\n|queer fish\n|quillfish\n|rabbitfish\n|ragfish\n|rainbowfish\n|ratfish\n|razorfish\n|redfish\n|reedfish\n|reef fish\n|ribbonfish\n|ricefish\n|robofish\n|rockfish\n|roosterfish\n|ropefish\n|roundfish\n|rudderfish\n|sablefish\n|sabrefish\n|salamanderfish\n|saltfish\n|sandfish\n|sawfish\n|scabbardfish,scabbard fish\n|scalefish\n|scorpionfish\n|sergeant fish\n|sheathfish\n|shellfish\n|shorefish\n|shovelfish\n|shrimpfish\n|silver dollar fish\n|silverfish\n|skatefish\n|skyfish\n|sleep with the fishes\n|snailfish\n|snakefish\n|snipefish\n|soapfish\n|soldierfish\n|so long, and thanks for all the fish\n|soup and fish,soup-and-fish\n|soup-and-fish suit\n|spadefish\n|spearfish\n|spikefish\n|spookfish\n|sportfish\n|spoutfish\n|squawfish\n|squirefish\n|squirrelfish\n|starfish\n|steakfish\n|stingfish\n|stockfish\n|stonefish\n|strange fish\n|studfish\n|suckerfish\n|suckfish\n|sunfish\n|swallowfish\n|swellfish\n|swim like a fish\n|swordfish\n|telescopefish\n|the cat would eat fish but would not wet her feet\n|the fish rots from the head\n|there are plenty more fish in the sea,there are plenty of fish in the sea\n|there's always a bigger fish\n|there's plenty more fish in the sea\n|thornfish\n|threadfish\n|Threefish\n|tigerfish\n|tilefish\n|tinfish,tin fish\n|toadfish\n|tofish\n|tonguefish\n|toothfish\n|torrentfish\n|towfish\n|treefish\n|triggerfish\n|trumpetfish\n|trunkfish\n|tunnyfish\n|turbofish\n|turkeyfish\n|underfish\n|unfishiness\n|unfishy\n|unicornfish\n|velvetfish\n|viperfish\n|wallfish\n|weakfish\n|weatherfish\n|wedgefish\n|weedfish\n|weeverfish\n|whalefish\n|what does that have to do with the price of fish\n|whistlefish\n|whitefish\n|wingfish\n|wolffish\n|wooden fish\n|wormfish\n|wreckfish\n|yellowfish\n|yellowtail reef fish\n|zebrafish\n}}\n\n=====Related terms=====\n* {{sense|adj}} [[fishly]], [[piscine]], [[fishy]] {{qualifier|inf.}}\n* {{sense|astronomical}} [[Fish]], [[Pisces]]\n* {{sense|collective}} [[piscifauna]]\n* {{sense|combinatorial form}} [[pisci-]] {{qualifier|Latinate|general}}\n* {{sense|fish-catcher}} ''See'' '''[[fisher]]'''\n* {{sense|fish-eater}} [[piscivore]]\n* {{sense|fish-infesting}} [[piscicolous]]\n* {{sense|fish-killing}} [[piscicidal]]\n* {{sense|fish-like}} [[fishly]], [[piscose]] {{qualifier|culinary}}, [[fishy]], [[fishlike]] {{qualifier|inf.}}\n* {{sense|fish science}} [[fishlore]], [[piscatology]] {{qualifier|irreg.}}\n* {{sense|fish-shaped}} [[pisciform]]\n* {{sense|fish vendor}} [[fishmonger]], [[piscitarian]]\n* {{sense|full of fish}} [[fishful]], [[pisculent]]\n* {{sense|skin disorder}} [[fish-skin disease]]\n* {{sense|state of being a fish}} [[fishdom]], [[fishhood]] {{qualifier|formal}}, [[piscinity]] {{qualifier|formal}}, [[fishiness]] {{qualifier|inf.}}\n*(''taxonomical''): [[Actinopterygii]], [[bony fish|bony fish,]] [[cartilaginous fish]], [[finned fish]], [[finfish]], {{taxfmt|Osteichthyes|superclass}}, [[Sarcopterygii]]\n\n=====Descendants=====\n* {{desc|srn|fisi}}\n* {{desc|bor=1|chn|pish}}\n* {{desc|bor=1|fi|fisu}}\n* {{desc|bor=1|zu|ufishi}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{see translation subpage|Noun}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nDeverbal from ''to fish'' (etymology 3).\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# A period of time spent fishing.\n#: {{ux|en|The '''fish''' at the lake didn't prove successful.}}\n# An instance of seeking something.\n#: {{ux|en|Merely two '''fishes''' for information told the whole story.}}\n\n===Etymology 3===\nFrom {{inh|en|ang|fiscian}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*fiskōn}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*fiskōną}}.\n{{col-top|2|cog}}\nCognate with {{cog|stq|fiskje||to fish}}, {{cog|nl|vissen||to fish}}, {{cog|de|fischen||to fish}}, {{cog|li|vésche}}, {{m|li|vèsse||to fish}}, {{cog|lb|fëschen||to fish}}, {{cog|da|-}}, {{cog|nb|-}} and {{cog|nn|fiske||to fish}}, {{cog|fo|-}}, {{cog|is|-}} and {{cog|sv|fiska||to fish}}, {{cog|got|𐍆𐌹𐍃𐌺𐍉𐌽||to fish}}.\n{{col-bottom}}\n\n====Verb====\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|en|intransitive|transitive}} To [[hunt]] fish or other [[aquatic]] animals in a [[body of water]], or to [[collect]] [[coral]] or [[pearl]]s from the bottom of the [[sea]].\n#: {{ux|en|We went '''fishing''' for crabs by the pier.}}\n#: {{ux|en|She went to the river to '''fish''' for trout.}}\n#* '''19th c.''', anonymous, \"The Bonny Ship the 'Diamond'\"\n#*: ''It's cheer up, my lads, let your hearts never fail,''\n#*: ''For the bonny ship the'' Diamond ''goes a-'''fishing''' for the whale.''\n#* {{quote-book|en|text=Thou hast '''fished''' salmon a thousand times, and mightst have taken a lesson.|last=Scott|first=Sir Walter|year=1828|title=The Fair Maid of Perth|chapter=V|page=133|url=https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/The_Fair_Maid_of_Perth/Chapter_V}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To search (a body of water) for something other than fish.\n#: {{ux|en|They '''fished''' the surrounding lakes for the dead body.}}\n# {{lb|en|fishing|transitive}} To use as [[bait]] when fishing.\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1983|title=The Fisherman Who Laughed|page=40|passage=`What you need are frogs,' said the veteran. `'''Fish''' them at night. There's nothing like them on big cork floats.'}}\n# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To (attempt to) find or get hold of an object by searching among other objects.\n#: {{syn|en|rummage}}\n#: {{ux|en|Why are you '''fishing''' through my things?}}\n#: {{ux|en|He was '''fishing''' for the keys in his pocket.}}\n# {{lb|en|intransitive|followed by \"for\" or \"around for\"}} To talk to people in an attempt to get them to say something, or seek to obtain something by [[artifice]].\n#: {{ux|en|The detective visited the local pubs '''fishing''' around for more information.}}\n#: {{ux|en|The actors loitered at the door, '''fishing''' for compliments.}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1820|author=w:Percy Bysshe Shelley|title=Oedipus Tyrannus; Or, Swellfoot The Tyrant: A Tragedy in Two Acts\n|passage=Laoctonos is '''fishing''' for a compliment,<br>But ’tis his due. Yes, you have drunk more wine,<br>And shed more blood, than any man in Thebes.}}\n# {{lb|en|intransitive|cricket}} Of a [[batsman]], to [[attempt]] to hit a ball [[outside]] off [[stump]] and [[miss]] it.\n# {{lb|en|nautical|transitive}} To repair (a spar or mast) by fastening a [[beam]] or other long object (often called a fish) over the damaged part (see [[fish#Noun|Noun]] above).\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1970|author=James Henderson|title=The Frigates, an account of the lesser warships of the wars from 1793 to 1815|publisher=Wordsworth|year_published=1998|page=143\n|passage={{...}} the crew were set to replacing and splicing the rigging and '''fishing''' the spars.}}\n# {{lb|en|nautical|transitive}} To hoist the flukes of.\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1860|title=Accounts and Papers of the House of Commons|page=214\n|passage=Found that the cause of the ship's having drifted on the night of the 19th, was from the bight of the chain span (used to '''fish''' the anchor,) having slipped between the shank and upper fluke, thereby preventing the lower fluke from opening {{...}}}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To draw or guide (a wire or cable) by means of [[fish tape]].\n\n=====Synonyms=====\n* {{sense|try to catch a fish}} [[angle]], [[drop in a line]]\n* {{sense|try to find something}} [[rifle]], [[rummage]]\n* {{sense|attempt to gain (compliments, etc)}} [[angle]]\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col|en|don't fish off the company dock\n|fishable\n|fish down\n|fished out\n|fisher|fish for compliments\n|fishery\n|fishline\n|fishnet\n|fishnet stockings\n|fish one's wish\n|fish out\n|fish up\n|underfished\n|unfished\n|you don't fish off the company pier\n}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|to catch fish or aquatic animals}}\n* Arabic: {{t+|ar|صَادَ}}\n*: Moroccan Arabic: {{t|ary|صيّد|tr=ṣayyəd}}\n* Armenian: {{t|hy|ձուկ բռնել}}\n* Aromanian: {{t|rup|piscuescu}}\n* Asturian: {{t|ast|pescar}}\n* Bangi: {{t|bni|lobo}}\n* Basque: {{t+|eu|arrantzan egin}}\n* Belarusian: {{t|be|рыба́чыць|impf}}, {{t|be|[[лаві́ць]] [[рыба|ры́бу]]|impf}}\n* Borôro: {{t|bor|wogu}}\n* Breton: {{t+|br|pesketa}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t|bg|[[ловя́]] [[ри́ба]]|impf}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|pescar}}\n* Cebuano: {{t|ceb|mamasol}}, {{t|ceb|mamukot}}, {{t|ceb|managat}}, {{t|ceb|mangisda}}\n* Cherokee: {{t|chr|ᎠᏧᎲᏍᎦ}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Cantonese: {{t|yue|釣魚|tr=diu3 jyu4-2}}\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|釣魚|tr=diàoyú}}, {{t+|cmn|漁|tr=yú}} {{q|literary, or used in compounds}}\n* Czech: {{t|cs|rybařit}}\n* Danish: {{t+|da|fiske}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|vissen}}, {{t+|nl|hengelen}}, {{t+|nl|snoeken}} {{qualifier|when fishing for this particular kind of fish}}\n* Egyptian: {{t-egy|ḥꜣm|h=HA-A-m-G51A}}\n* Esperanto: {{t|eo|fiŝkapti}}\n* Fijian: {{t|fj|siwa}}, {{t|fj|qoli}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|kalastaa}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|pêcher}} {{q|transitive}}\n* Frisian:\n*: West Frisian: {{t|fy|fiskje}}\n* Friulian: {{t|fur|pescjâ}}, {{t|fur|pesčhâ}}\n* Galician: {{t+|gl|pescar}}\n* German: {{t+|de|fischen}}, {{t+|de|angeln}}\n* Gothic: {{t|got|𐍆𐌹𐍃𐌺𐍉𐌽}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|ψαρεύω}}, {{t+|el|αλιεύω}}\n*: Ancient Greek: {{t|grc|ἁλιεύω}}\n* Greenlandic: {{t|kl|aalisarpoq}}\n* Guarani:\n*: Paraguayan Guarani: {{t-check|gug|kutu}} {{qualifier|transitive}}, {{t-check|gug|pirakutu}} {{qualifier|intransitive}}\n* Hawaiian: {{t|haw|lawaiʻa}}\n* Hmong:\n*: White Hmong: {{t|mww|nuv ntses}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|halászik}}\n* Icelandic: {{t+|is|veiða}} {{qualifier|also ‘hunt’}}, {{t+|is|fiska}} {{qualifier|less common}}\n* Ido: {{t+|io|peskar}}\n* Indonesian: {{t+|id|memancing}}\n* Interlingua: {{t|ia|piscar}}\n* Irish:\n*: Old Irish: {{t|sga|ad·claid}}\n* Istriot: {{t|ist|pascà}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|pescare}}\n* Japanese: {{t+|ja|釣る|tr=tsuru}}\n* Kabuverdianu: {{t|kea|piska}}, {{t|kea|peská}}\n* Kaingang: {{t|kgp|vim ke}}\n* Kashmiri: {{t+|ks|گاڈ}}\n* Khmer: {{t+|km|នេសាទ}}\n* Kituba: {{t|ktu|loba}}\n* Kongo: {{t|kg|loba}}\n* Korean: {{t+|ko|낚다}} {{q|transitive}}, {{t+|ko|낚시하다}} {{q|intransitive}}\n* Lao: {{t|lo|ປະມົງ}}\n* Latin: {{t|la|piscor}}\n* Latvian: {{t+|lv|zvejot}}, {{t+|lv|makšķerēt}}\n* Lingala: {{t|ln|lobo}}, {{t|ln|lúba}}\n* Lithuanian: {{t|lt|žvejoti}}, {{t|lt|žuvauti}}, {{t|lt|meškerioti}}\n* Lombard: {{t|lmo|pescà}}\n* Luxembourgish: {{t+|lb|fëschen}}\n* Malay: {{t|ms|[[tangkap|menangkap ikan]]}}, {{t|ms|[[pancing|memancing]]}} {{qualifier|angling}}\n* Malayalam: {{t|ml|മീൻപിടിക്കുക}}\n* Māori: {{t|mi|hī}} {{qualifier|with a hook}}, {{t|mi|matira}} {{qualifier|with a rod}}, {{t|mi|hao}} {{qualifier|with a net}}, {{t|mi|māngoingoi}} {{qualifier|with a line}}, {{t|mi|makamaka}} {{qualifier|with a hook and line}}, {{t|mi|makamaka ika}} {{qualifier|with a hook and line}}\n* Middle English: {{t|enm|fisshen}}\n* Mwani: {{t|wmw|kuvuwa}}\n* Nahuatl:\n*: Classical Nahuatl: {{t|nci|*michahci}}, {{t|nci|michma}}\n* Norman: {{t|nrf|pêtchi}} {{qualifier|Jersey}}\n* Norwegian: {{t+|no|fiske}}\n* Occitan: {{t+|oc|pescar}}\n* Ohlone:\n*: Southern Ohlone: {{t|css|huynina}}\n* Old English: {{t|ang|fiscian}}\n* Persian: {{t|fa|ماهی‌گیری|tr=mâhi-giri}}\n* Polish: {{t|pl|łowić ryby}}, {{t+|pl|wędkować|impf}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|pescar}} {{q|ambitransitive}}\n* Quechua: {{t|qu|challway}}\n* Romani:\n*: Kalo Finnish Romani: {{t|rmf|matšalaa}}\n* Romanian: {{t+|ro|pescui}}\n* Romansh: {{t|rm|pestgar}}, {{t|rm|pescar}}, {{t|rm|pastgear}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|рыба́чить|impf}}, {{t|ru|[[лови́ть]] [[рыба|ры́бу]]|impf}}\n* Sardinian: {{t|sc|piscae}}, {{t|sc|piscai}}, {{t|sc|piscare}}\n* Serbo-Croatian: {{t+|sh|pecati|impf}}, {{t+|sh|upecati|pf}}\n* Shor: {{t|cjs|палықтарға|tr=palıqtarğa}}\n* Slovene: {{t+|sl|ribariti}}, {{t|sl|loviti ribe}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|pescar}} {{q|transitive}}\n* Sranan Tongo: {{t|srn|fisi}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|fiska}}\n* Thai: {{t|th|ตกปลา}}, {{t+|th|ประมง}}\n* Tok Pisin: {{t|tpi|huk}}\n* Turkish: {{t|tr|balık tutmak}}\n* Ukrainian: {{t+|uk|риба́лити|impf}}, {{t|uk|[[лови́ти]] [[риба|ри́бу]]|impf}}\n* Vietnamese: {{t+|vi|câu cá}}\n* Walloon: {{t+|wa|pexhî}}\n* Welsh: {{t+|cy|pysgota}}\n* Yoruba: {{t|yo|pẹja}} {{qualifier|intransitive}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|transitive: to try to find something in a body of water}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|kalastaa}}, {{t+|fi|onkia}}, {{t+|fi|naarata}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|ψαρεύω}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|лови́ть|impf}}, {{t+|ru|вы́ловить|pf}}\n* Walloon: {{t+|wa|rapexhî}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|to attempt to find by searching among other objects}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|penkoa}}\n* Interlingua: {{t-check|ia|piscar}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|pescar}}, {{t+|pt|catar}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|выу́живать|impf}}, {{t+|ru|выу́дить|pf}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|to attempt to obtain information by talking to people}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|urkkia}}, {{t+|fi|onkia}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|ψαρεύω}}\n* Icelandic: {{t|is|veiða upp úr}}, {{t+|is|fiska}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|выу́живать|impf}}, {{t+|ru|выу́дить|pf}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|cricket: to attempt to hit outside off stump and miss}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|to attempt to gain something}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|kalastella}}, {{t+|fi|kerjätä}}, {{t+|fi|vongata}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|выла́вливать|impf}}, {{t+|ru|вы́ловить|pf}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|nautical: to repair by beam or similar long object}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Etymology 4===\nBorrowed from {{bor|en|fr|fiche||peg, mark}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# {{lb|en|obsolete}} A [[counter]], used in various [[game]]s.\n\n===References===\n* {{R:Webster 1913}}\n<references/>\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{pedia|fish (disambiguation)}}\n* {{pedia}}\n* {{pedia|fish (food)}}\n* {{pedia|fishing}}\n\n{{C|en|Fish}}\n\n==Middle English==\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|enm|noun|altform=1}}\n\n# {{alt form|enm|fisch}}"}}